message.text:
#Hiragana Master
Say it Together! Basic Japanese Words in Japanese Alphabetical Order.
Today's Word is "YO" YOPPARAI　#nihongo
日本の単語を五十音順にわかりやすく紹介！「よ」っぱらい（酔っ払い、drunken person)

Spring in Japan is a season of Yopparai, a drunken person!?
March and April are the end/beginning of school semester/fiscal year, and it is the right time for Hanami (literally "flower viewing", often meaning drinking party under cherry blossoms), so we have many drinking parties.

It is said that farmers used to have Hanami to estimate their harvest of a year by seeing how cherry blossoms bloomed. If the result was good fortune, they drank to celebrate, and if the result was bad, they drank to drive off evil spirits. Either way, everyone drank alcohols.

Maybe Japanese is good at finding good excuse to have a drinking party?
Please don't drink too much and be a "happy" yopparai, everyone!
--------------------------
春は「酔っ払い」の季節？？
3月、4月は年度の変わり目、しかもお花見シーズンで、飲み会が多い時期。

昔の農家では、桜の咲き方でその年の収穫を占っていて、結果が吉とでたらお酒を飲んで祝い、凶がでたらお酒を飲んで厄払いをしたそうです。つまりどちらにしてもお酒を飲んでいたということ。

もしかしたら、日本人はお酒を飲むいい言い訳を見つけるのがうまいのかもしれませんね。
皆さん、飲み方には注意して、「ハッピーな酔っ払い」で！

message.text:
April is a month of "Fresh Start"!
新しい気持ちになる日本の４月！

In Japan, school semester/ business year start in April, so it is full of new encounter such as new friends/co-workers, new class room/office, new shoes, new uniform/suits...whole new environment!

We, the Japan Foundation, also welcomed new members at the office from today, blooming with dream and hope, like the full bloom of cherry blossoms!

Congratulations to everyone who has started the new life stage!

日本の学校や会社では、４月が新しい年の始まりです。
新しい出会いがたくさん。新しい友達、同僚、教室やオフィス、新しい靴に制服、スーツ・・・本当に新鮮な気分！

国際交流基金にも新しい職員がたくさん入りましたよ。夢と希望を胸に、今ちょうど満開を迎えた桜のように輝いた笑顔できてくれました！
新しいスタートを迎えた皆さま、おめでとうございます！
http://words.marugotoweb.jp/search_detail.php?id=1842&p=1&q=%E5%85%A5%E5%AD%A6&source=search&lang=en

message.text:
#Hiragana Master
Say it Together! Basic Japanese Words in Japanese Alphabetical Order.
Today's Word is "YU" YUBI　#nihongo
日本の単語を五十音順にわかりやすく紹介！「ゆ」び（指、finger)
http://eng.nihongodecarenavi.jp/jpn/search-list.php?cmd=search&q=%E3%82%86%E3%81%B3

As many other languages do, Japanese often uses body parts as idioms.
Speaking of Yubi, these are some expressions.
"Yubi Ori Kazoeru", literally meaning "to count the days on one's fingers", which often comes with "wait" meaning looking forward to do something.
"Yubi wo Kuwaeru", literally meaning "to put your finger in your mouth", which means looking on enviously.
"Yubi Kiri wo Suru", literally meaning "finger cut-off", which means making a pledge by linking little fingers.

My favorite one with other body part is "Komimi ni Hasamu （こみみにはさむ、小耳に挟む）", literally meaning "sandwich something between your small ears", which means "to happen to hear", because we can not actually do that, but still DO use it a lot!

Is there any unique expressions in your language or favorite idioms in Japanese using body parts ? Please share it!
-----------------------------
皆さんが使う言葉にも、たぶんたくさんあるのでは？　体の一部を使った熟語！
例えば「指（ゆび）」を使った日本語の熟語はこんな表現があります。

「指折り数える」（待ち遠しい気持ちを表す言葉）
「指をくわえる」（うらやましがりながら、何もできない様子を表す言葉）
「指切りをする」（約束をする時に使う言葉）


体の他の部分を使った私のお気に入りの表現は、「小耳に挟む」（聞くつもりがないのに聞いてしまう、ちょっと聞く）です！実際には耳にはさむなんてできないのに・・・って思うとおもしろくないですか？

皆さんが使う言葉や日本語で、体の一部を使ったお気に入りの言葉、教えてください！
